VThe first idea I'd like to suggest is that we all
p4
aVlove music a great deal. It means a lot to us.
p5
aVBut music is even more powerful if you don't just listen to it, but you make it yourself.
p6
aVSo, that's my first idea. And we all know about the Mozart effect \u2014
p7
aVthe idea that's been around for the last five to 10 years \u2014
p8
aVthat just by listening to music or by playing music to your baby [in utero],
p9
aVthat it'll raise our IQ points 10, 20, 30 percent.
p10
aa(lp11
VGreat idea, but it doesn't work at all.
p12
aVSo, you can't just listen to music, you have to make it somehow.
p13
aVAnd I'd add to that, that it's not just making it,
p14
aVbut everybody, each of us, everybody in the world
p15
aVhas the power to create and be part of music in a very dynamic way,
p16
aVand that's one of the main parts of my work.
p17
aVSo, with the MIT Media Lab, for quite a while now,
p18
aVwe've been engaged in a field called active music.
p19
aVWhat are all the possible ways that we can think of
p20
aVto get everybody in the middle of a musical experience,
p21
aVnot just listening, but making music?
p22
aa(lp23
VAnd we started by making instruments for some of the world's greatest performers \u2014
p24
aVwe call these hyperinstruments \u2014 for Yo-Yo Ma, Peter Gabriel, Prince,
p25
aVorchestras, rock bands. Instruments where they're all kinds of sensors
p26
aVbuilt right into the instrument, so the instrument knows how it's being played.
p27
aVAnd just by changing the interpretation and the feeling,
p28
aVI can turn my cello into a voice, or into a whole orchestra,
p29
aVor into something that nobody has ever heard before.
p30
aa(lp31
VWhen we started making these, I started thinking, why can't we make
p32
aVwonderful instruments like that for everybody,
p33
aVpeople who aren't fantastic Yo-Yo Mas or Princes?
p34
aVSo, we've made a whole series of instruments.
p35
aVOne of the largest collections is called the Brain Opera.
p36
aVIt's a whole orchestra of about 100 instruments,
p37
aVall designed for anybody to play using natural skill.
p38
aVSo, you can play a video game, drive through a piece of music,
p39
aVuse your body gesture to control huge masses of sound,
p40
aVtouch a special surface to make melodies, use your voice to make a whole aura.
p41
aVAnd when we make the Brain Opera, we invite the public to come in,
p42
aVto try these instruments and then collaborate with us
p43
aVto help make each performance of the Brain Opera.
p44
aVWe toured that for a long time. It is now permanently in Vienna,
p45
aVwhere we built a museum around it.
